#### Games

Merlin has also found his way into the digital realm, often as a playable character or a significant plot device.

*   In *[Age of Wonders II](/Age_of_Wonders_II)* and *[Age of Wonders: Shadow Magic](/Age_of_Wonders:_Shadow_Magic)*, Merlin is a playable character.
*   In *[Curses](/Curses_(video_game))*, Merlin plays a pivotal role in the game's historical narrative.
*   * [Fate/Grand Order](/Fate/Grand_Order)* features Merlin as a playable Caster-class servant. His female "Prototype" counterpart, Lady Avalon, also appears.
*   The arcade game *[Gauntlet](/Gauntlet_(arcade_game))* included Merlin as one of its four playable heroes, a role he continued into *Gauntlet 4*.
*   In *[Blazing Dragons](/Blazing_Dragons_(video_game))*, Merlin, reimagined as Mervin, is Sir George's wizard companion and antagonist, voiced by [Rob Paulsen](/Rob_Paulsen).
*   The Disney iteration of Merlin appears in the *[Kingdom Hearts](/Kingdom_Hearts)* series, including *[Kingdom Hearts II](/Kingdom_Hearts_II)*, *[Kingdom Hearts Birth by Sleep](/Kingdom_Hearts_Birth_by_Sleep)*, and *[Kingdom Hearts III](/Kingdom_Hearts_III)*, maintaining his appearance from *[The Sword in the Stone](/The_Sword_in_the_Stone_(1963_film))*. While silent in the first game, he's voiced by [Jeff Bennett](/Jeff_Bennett) in the sequel.
*   In the role-playing game *[Magic and Mayhem](/Magic_and_Mayhem)*, Merlin serves as the game's final [antagonist](/Antagonist).
*   *[Master of Magic](/Master_of_Magic)* includes Merlin as one of its predefined wizards.
*   The [MMORPG](/MMORPG) *[RuneScape](/RuneScape)* features Merlin in three quests: "Merlin's Crystal," "The Holy Grail," and "King's Ransom."
*   In *[Sonic and the Black Knight](/Sonic_and_the_Black_Knight)*, the character Merlina is based on Merlin, who is also her grandfather.
*   The 2013 video game *[Soul Sacrifice](/Soul_Sacrifice_(video_game))*, and its sequel *[Soul Sacrifice Delta](/Soul_Sacrifice_Delta)*, feature Merlin as the antagonist, known as the Magusar.
*   In the [MMORPG](/MMORPG) *[Wizard101](/Wizard101)*, Merlin, under the guise of "Merle Ambrose," is the headmaster of Ravenwood School of Magical Arts.
*   *[Young Merlin](/Young_Merlin)* allows players to experience Merlin's youth.
*   In *[Zoda's Revenge: StarTropics II](/Zoda%27s_Revenge:_StarTropics_II)*, Merlin grants the protagonist, Mike, psychic abilities.
*   In *[The Resistance](/The_Resistance_(game))* (Avalon variant), Merlin is secretly identified as one of the good players and must subtly guide the team without revealing his identity.
*   *[SMITE: Battleground of the Gods](/Smite_(video_game))* includes Merlin as a playable character.
*   *[Lego Marvel Super Heroes 2](/Lego_Marvel_Super_Heroes_2)* features Merlin in a side mission and as a playable character.
*   In *[Disney Dreamlight Valley](/Disney_Dreamlight_Valley)*, the Disney version of Merlin appears as a villager and guide.
*   *[Hogwarts Legacy](/Hogwarts_Legacy)* incorporates "Trials of Merlin" as puzzles that grant players extra inventory space.

#### Literature

Merlin's literary presence is vast, spanning centuries and genres, often reimagining his role and nature.

*   The 1622 play *[The Birth of Merlin](/The_Birth_of_Merlin)* by [William Rowley](/William_Rowley) presents Merlin as the son of the [Devil](/Devil), who eventually becomes an advisor to King Uther.
*   [Mark Twain](/Mark_Twain)'s 1889 novel *[A Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court](/A_Connecticut_Yankee_in_King_Arthur%27s_Court)* initially portrays Merlin as a charlatan satirizing [superstition](/Superstition), but later grants him genuine magical abilities.
*   [C.S. Lewis](/C._S._Lewis) incorporated Merlin Ambrosius into his 1946 novel *[That Hideous Strength](/That_Hideous_Strength)*, the third book in *[The Space Trilogy](/The_Space_Trilogy)*. Here, Merlin awakens after centuries to combat the forces of evil, his connection to angelic powers intact from a time when sorcery was not yet corrupted. Lewis also makes a nod to [J.R.R. Tolkien's](/J._R._R._Tolkien) "Numinor" through Merlin's mention of it.
*   In [John Cowper Powys'](/John_Cowper_Powys) 1951 novel *[Porius: A Romance of the Dark Ages](/Porius:_A_Romance_of_the_Dark_Ages)*, [Myrddin Wyllt](/Myrddin_Wyllt), or Merlin the Wild, is a central figure and counselor to Emperor Arthur, identified with [Cronos](/Cronus), or [Saturn](/Saturn_(mythology)). Powys also features Merlin in *[A Glastonbury Romance](/A_Glastonbury_Romance)* (1934) and *Morwyn* (1937).
*   The 1955 novel *Merlín e Familia* by [Galician](/Galicia_(Spain)) author [Álvaro Cunqueiro](/%C3%81lvaro_Cunqueiro) places Merlin in the Galician forest of Esmelle, where mythical figures seek his counsel, blending Arthurian legend with local folklore.
*   [Susan Cooper's](/Susan_Cooper) *[The Dark Is Rising](/The_Dark_Is_Rising_Sequence)* series (1965–1977) centers on Merlin as a key figure in the battle between "the Dark and the Light." He is known by various names, including "Gummerry" (Great Uncle Merry) and Professor Merriman Lyon.
*   [T.H. White's](/T._H._White) 1958 retelling, *[The Once and Future King](/The_Once_and_Future_King)*, presents "Merlyn" as living backward in time, a curious affliction echoed in [Dan Simmons'](/Dan_Simmons) *[Hyperion](/Hyperion_(Simmons_novel))* as the "Merlin sickness." White's related novel, *[The Book of Merlyn](/The_Book_of_Merlin)*, was published in 1977.
*   [Mary Stewart's](/Mary_Stewart_(novelist)) Merlin Trilogy (1970–1979) features Myrddin Emrys (Merlin Ambrosius) as the protagonist of the first two books, *[The Crystal Cave](/The_Crystal_Cave)* (1970) and *[The Hollow Hills](/The_Hollow_Hills)* (1973), drawing heavily on earlier traditions. The latter books focus more on Arthur and [Mordred](/Mordred), though still from Merlin's perspective. Stewart posits Aurelius Ambrosius as Merlin's father, making him Arthur's cousin, and ultimately depicts Merlin driven mad by [Morgause's](/Morgause) poison.
*   [Andre Norton's](/Andre_Norton) 1975 novel *Merlin's Mirror* tells the story of a half-human, half-alien Merlin.
*   [Robert Nye's](/Robert_Nye) 1978 novel *Merlin* offers a deliberately bawdy and anti-Christian take on the Arthurian legend, recounting Merlin's experiences after being imprisoned by [Nimue](/Lady_of_the_Lake). It draws from earlier texts and incorporates elements of [Kabbalah](/Kaballah) alongside explicit content.
*   [Roger Zelazny's](/Roger_Zelazny) 1979 short story "The Last Defender of Camelot" features Merlin as a modern-day villain. It won the 1980 [Balrog Award](/Balrog_Award) and was adapted into an episode of *[The Twilight Zone](/The_Twilight_Zone)* in 1986.
*   [Michael de Angelo's](/Michael_de_Angelo) 1979 work *[Cyr Myrddin, the Coming of Age of Merlin](/Cyr_Myrddin,_the_Coming_of_Age_of_Merlin)* chronicles Merlin's early life and search for destiny.
*   In [Tim Powers'](/Tim_Powers) 1979 novel *The Drawing of the Dark*, Merlin, identified as Aurelianus, aids in the reincarnation of King Arthur to battle Eastern forces in 16th-century Vienna.
*   [Stephen King](/Stephen_King) references a character named Maerlyn in *The Dark Tower* series (starting 1982) and the prequel comic *[The Gunslinger Born](/The_Gunslinger_Born)* (2007). This Maerlyn, an advisor to an alternate Arthur, is depicted as evil, fathering the sorcerer [Marten Broadcloak](/Marten_Broadcloak) and creating the soul-corrupting Wizard's Rainbow.
*   [Marion Zimmer Bradley's](/Marion_Zimmer_Bradley) 1983 novel *[The Mists of Avalon](/The_Mists_of_Avalon)* retells the Arthurian legend from [Morgan Le Fay's](/Morgan_Le_Fay) perspective. The novel features two successive characters holding the title "The Merlin of Britain," leaders of the [Druids](/Druid).
*   [René Barjavel's](/Ren%C3%A9_Barjavel) 1984 novel *L'Enchanteur* explores the Knights of the Round Table and the quest for the Holy Grail through the lens of Merlin's relationship with the Lady of the Lake.
*   Arthurian scholar [Nikolai Tolstoy](/Nikolai_Tolstoy) authored *The Quest For Merlin* (1985), a non-fiction work, and the historical fantasy *[The Coming of the King](/The_Coming_of_the_King)* (1988), which depicts Merlin living after Arthur's death.
*   [Michel Rio's](/Michel_Rio) 1989 novel *Merlin* portrays Merlin as a strategist and advisor, not primarily a wizard, and later as Morgana's teacher. It's part of a trilogy that includes *Morgane* (1999) and *Arthur* (2002).
*   Merlin is a key character in [Mary Pope Osborne's](/Mary_Pope_Osborne) *[Magic Tree House](/Magic_Tree_House)* children's book series, appearing in "The Merlin Missions" volumes starting in 1992.
*   [Stephen R. Lawhead's](/Stephen_R._Lawhead) *[Pendragon Cycle](/Pendragon_Cycle)* series features Merlin (Myrddin) as the narrator in the 1988 novel *Merlin* and the 1994 novel *Pendragon*. Lawhead reimagines him as a half-Atlantean king of [Dyfed](/Kingdom_of_Dyfed) who experiences madness before becoming a prophet, advisor, and bard.
*   [Jack Whyte's](/Jack_Whyte) nine-volume *[The Camulod Chronicles](/The_Camulod_Chronicles)* (1992–2005) offers a naturalistic retelling of the Arthurian legend, providing rational explanations for Merlin's supposed magical abilities.
*   In [Robert Weinberg's](/Robert_Weinberg_(author)) novels *A Logical Magician* (1994) and *A Calculated Magic* (1996), Merlin is presented as a being brought into existence by collective belief, his powers derived from what people believe him to be.
*   [Fred Saberhagen's](/Fred_Saberhagen) 1995 novel *Merlin's Bones* is partly narrated from the perspective of a young Merlin.
*   [Bernard Cornwell's](/Bernard_Cornwell) *[The Warlord Chronicles]* (1995–1997) depicts Merlin as a [druid](/Druid) ruling over Avalon from his seat on [Ynys Wydryn](/Ynys_Wydryn).
*   [T.A. Barron](/T.A._Barron) explores Merlin's youth in *[The Lost Years of Merlin](/The_Lost_Years_of_Merlin)* series (starting 1996) and his adulthood in the sequel series *[The Great Tree of Avalon](/Child_of_the_Dark_Prophecy)*.
*   [Jane Yolen's](/Jane_Yolen) Young Merlin Trilogy (1996–1997)—*Passager*, *Hobby*, and *Merlin*—reimagines Merlin's boyhood, detailing his abandonment and discovery of his powers.
*   [J.K. Rowling](/J.K._Rowling) elevates Merlin to near-divine status in her *[Harry Potter](/Harry_Potter)* series (1997–2007), calling him "The Prince of Enchanters." The expression "Merlin's Beard" is used as an exclamation. The "Order of Merlin" is an award similar to an [OBE](/Order_of_the_British_Empire). According to [Pottermore](/Pottermore), Merlin founded the Order to protect [Muggles](/Muggle). He's also featured on a Famous Witches and Wizards Collectors card. [Albus Dumbledore](/Albus_Dumbledore) is noted for his resemblance to Merlin. As is typical, Merlin is positioned as the enemy of [Morgan le Fay](/Morgan_le_Fay). Interestingly, [Pottermore](/Pottermore) claims Merlin was a [Slytherin](/Slytherin), a notion that clashes with his historical placement centuries before Hogwarts' founding.
*   [Jim Butcher's](/Jim_Butcher) *[The Dresden Files](/The_Dresden_Files)* series (starting 2000) uses "Merlin" as both a title (leader of the White Council) and the name of the individual responsible for creating the supernatural prison Demonreach.
*   [Robert Holdstock's](/Robert_Holdstock) *The Merlin Codex* trilogy (2001–2006) chronicles Merlin's adventures across Europe over two millennia, placing him alongside figures like [Jason and the Argonauts](/Jason) and [Urtha Pendragon](/Uther_Pendragon). Holdstock also wrote the short novel *[Merlin's Wood](/Merlin%27s_Wood)* (1994).
*   In [Diana Wynne Jones'](/Diana_Wynne_Jones) 2003 book *[The Merlin Conspiracy](/The_Merlin_Conspiracy)*, Merlin is a title rather than a person, representing the guardian of a kingdom's magical health.
*   [Simon Green's](/Simon_R._Green) Nightside series (2003–2012) features Merlin Satanspawn, son of the [Devil](/Devil) and a friend to King Arthur.
*   The romantic urban fantasy series *[Enchanted, Inc.](/Enchanted,_Inc.)* (starting 2005) by [Shanna Swendson](/Shanna_Swendson) identifies Merlin as the [CEO](/Chief_executive_officer) of Magic, Spells, and Illusions, Inc.
*   [Sherrilyn Kenyon](/Sherrilyn_Kenyon), writing as Kinley MacGregor, includes "Penmerlin Emrys" in her Lords of Avalon series (2006–2018).
*   Books based on the British TV show *[Merlin](/Merlin_(TV_series))* (2008) focus on an adolescent Merlin in King Uther's Camelot.
*   [James A. Owen's](/James_A._Owen) *[The Indigo King](/The_Indigo_King)* (2008), part of the *[Chronicles of the Imaginarium Geographica](/Chronicles_of_the_Imaginarium_Geographica)* series, presents Merlin as an antagonist and the Cartographer of the Imaginarium Geographica. He is depicted as ambitious and treacherous, banished from the Archipelago of Dreams for attempting to manipulate the future. He later travels to [Albion](/Albion) (Britain) and becomes the apparent father of Arthur through the [Lady of the Lake](/Lady_of_the_Lake).
*   In [James Rollins'](/James_Rollins) 2009 novel *The Doomsday Key*, Bardsey Island is described as the burial place of [Fomorian](/Fomorian) royalty and famous [Druid](/Druid) priests, including Merlin.
*   Kristine Papin Morris explores Merlin's childhood in her Merlin of Carmarthen series, featuring *Merlin of Carmarthen* (2010) and *Merlin of Calidon* (2013).
*   The Arkwell Academy series by Mindee Arnett (starting 2013) positions Merlin as the main antagonist, seeking a powerful sword.
*   In the *[High School DxD](/High_School_DxD)* light novel series, Merlin Ambrosius is credited with founding human magic by studying demon magic, making him the first human magician.
*   [Theodore Sturgeon's](/Theodore_Sturgeon) 1951 short story "Excalibur and the Atom" places Merlin Ambrosius and Arthurian mythology within a [science fiction](/Science_fiction) context.
*   In Gabriel Estes's *The Seven Deadly Sins, Book 1: The First Hunt* (2021), Merlin is a sorcerer in Caerleon who bestows a [grimoire](/Grimoire) upon Exevalathor. He is later revealed to be [Satan](/Satan), the Sin of Wrath, weakened by its presence.

#### Music, musicals, and operas

Merlin's resonance extends to the auditory arts, with numerous musical interpretations.

*   [Karl Goldmark's](/Karl_Goldmark) opera *[Merlin](/Merlin_(Goldmark))* premiered in 1886.
*   [Isaac Albéniz's](/Isaac_Alb%C3%A9niz) opera *[Merlin](/Merlin_(opera))* was completed in 1902 but not premiered until 2004, offering a staged rendition of Arthurian legend with significant dramatic alterations.
*   The musical *[Camelot](/Camelot_(musical))* has featured various actors as Merlyn, including [David Hurst](/David_Hurst), [Louis Turenne](/Louis_Turenne), [Laurence Naismith](/Laurence_Naismith) (in the 1967 film adaptation), James Valentine, and James A. Stephens.
*   [Rick Wakeman's](/Rick_Wakeman) 1975 album *[The Myths and Legends of King Arthur and the Knights of the Round Table](/The_Myths_and_Legends_of_King_Arthur_and_the_Knights_of_the_Round_Table)* includes "Merlin, the Magician" as its fourth track.
*   *[Merlin](/Merlin_(musical))* (1983) was a [Broadway musical](/Broadway_musical) featuring illusionist [Doug Henning](/Doug_Henning) with music by [Elmer Bernstein](/Elmer_Bernstein).
*   A fictionalized Merlin appears on [Ayreon's](/Ayreon) debut album *[The Final Experiment](/The_Final_Experiment)* (1995).
*   [Bob Catley](/Bob_Catley) of [Magnum](/Magnum_(band)) portrayed Merlin in Gary Hughes's [rock operas](/Rock_opera) *[Once and Future King Part I](/Once_and_Future_King_Part_I)* and *[Once and Future King Part II](/Once_and_Future_King_Part_II)* (2003).
*   *[Merlin – Bard of the Unseen](/Merlin_%E2%80%93_Bard_of_the_Unseen)* (2003) is a [concept album](/Concept_album) by [progressive rock](/Progressive_rock) band [Kayak](/Kayak_(band)), expanding upon their 1981 album *[Merlin](/Merlin_(Kayak_album))*.
*   In the 2015 French musical *[La Légende du Roi Arthur](/La_L%C3%A9gende_du_roi_Arthur)*, David Alexis played Merlin.

#### Television

Merlin's presence on the small screen is perhaps the most extensive, with countless portrayals across various genres.

*   *[The Pendragon Cycle: Rise of the Merlin](/The_Pendragon_Cycle:_Rise_of_the_Merlin)* (2026) will feature Tom Sharp as Merlin.
